Actually, if `f(n) = k`, then for `a = b = 1`, we need `k | 1 - k^k`, which can't hold for `k > 1`. 

Indeed, if `k > 1`, then `1 - k^k ≡ 1 mod k`, so `k` cannot divide `1 - k^k` unless `k = 1`. 

Thus, the only constant `Bonza` function is `f(n) = 1`. 

